04212nam a22006015i 9780822393146DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223931467 a10.1515/97808223931462doi  a(DE-B1597)553737  a(OCoLC)1110286419  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS479 7aHIS0170002bisacsh1 aRoy, Parama, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAlimentary Tracts :bAppetites, Aversions, and the Postcolonial /cParama Roy; ed. by Robyn Wiegman, Caren Kaplan, Inderpal Grewal. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies : 4400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Disgust -- t2. Abstinence -- t3. Dearth -- t4. Appetite -- tRemains -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Alimentary Tracts Parama Roy argues that who eats and with whom, who starves, and what is rejected as food are questions fundamental to empire, decolonization, and globalization. In crucial ways, she suggests, colonialism reconfigured the sensorium of colonizer and colonized, generating novel experiences of desire, taste, and appetite as well as new technologies of the embodied self. For colonizers, Indian nationalists, diasporic persons, and others in the colonial and postcolonial world orders, the alimentary tract functioned as an important corporeal, psychoaffective, and ethicopolitical contact zone, in which questions of identification, desire, difference, and responsibility were staged.Interpreting texts that have addressed cooking, dining, taste, hungers, excesses, and aversions in South Asia and its diaspora since the mid-nineteenth century, Roy relates historical events and literary figures to tropes of disgust, abstention, dearth, and appetite. She analyzes the fears of pollution and deprivation conveyed in British accounts of the so-called Mutiny of 1857, complicates understandings of Mohandas K. Gandhi’s vegetarianism, examines the “famine fictions” of the novelist-actor Mahasweta Devi, and reflects on the diasporic cookbooks and screen performances of Madhur Jaffrey. This account of richly visceral global modernity furnishes readers with a new idiom for understanding historical action and cultural transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBritishzIndiaxHistory. 0aFood habitsxPolitical aspectszIndia. 0aPolitics and culture. 0aPostcolonialismzIndia. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh1 aGrewal, Inderpal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaplan, Caren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393146zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393146423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822393146/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles